                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The Fountainhead by Ayn Rand - great read.
<br />

<br />
Also if you liked the Erdos biography (I'm assuming the mathamatician Erdos) I recommend picking up 'Godel, Escher, Bach: An Eternal Golden Braid' by Douglas Hoffstader. Note that Godel has two little dot thingies over the o so don't be confused. It's an amazing read and full of interesting and fun ideas. It's long so don't plan on getting through it in a day, or even a week. Personally I tackled it a bit at a time while reading something else, but it's broken down chapter by chapter so you don't miss much if anything by taking it slow.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />When a government has ceased to protect the lives, liberty and property of the people, from whom its legitimate powers are derived, and for the advancement of whose happiness it was instituted, and so far from being a guarantee for the enjoyment of those inestimable and inalienable rights, becomes an instrument in the hands of evil rulers for their oppression. - Declaration of Independence of the State of Texas.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
