                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The Dan Brown books, DaVinci Code and Angels and Demons are fantastic. Has anyone not read them yet?
<br />

<br />
IMHO, the best Ayn Rand book is "Atlas Shrugged".
<br />

<br />
It seems you read a fairly diverse cross-section of works, try these:
<br />

<br />
Tim O'Brien : The Things They Carried. Simply a stunning novel.
<br />

<br />
Kurt Vonnegut: Cat's Cradle. 
<br />

<br />
Haruki Murakami: The Wild Sheep Chase and Dance, Dance, Dance. Murakami is a genious, and one of the most original writers I have ever had the pleasure to read. I guarantee, you have never read anyhting like him.
<br />

<br />
Elizabeth Peters: The Amelia Peabody series. Tremendously entertaining series which centers on Egyptology....these books are like good friends.
<br />

<br />
Amos Oz: The Same Sea. Perhaps the most beautifully crafted novel I have ever read. Oz blends the line between poetry and prose in the most powerful and seamless manner I have ever seen...and the result is frankly, well, a gift.
<br />

<br />
If you like sci-fi, read "Hyperion" by Dan Simmons...you will thank me.
<br />

<br />
If you like fantasy, read George R.R. martin's "The Songs of Ice and Fire" series, you will curse me because you will do nothing but read them until you are done.
<br />

<br />
Other Notables:
<br />

<br />
Jim Thompson: "The Killer Inside Me"
<br />

<br />
James Ellroy: "L.A. Confidential"</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
