                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Read The Fountainhead, but realize you are reading propoganda.  Treat it like you would reading the foundation myth of a religious sect.
<br />

<br />
Don't read Atlas Shrugged unless you have a higher tolerance for bad sex scenes than I do.  =)
<br />

<br />
I've heard <span style="font-style: italic">"Surely Youre Joking, Mr. Feynman!"</span> is an interesting read.
<br />

<br />
I'll toss out another vote for RR Martin's series, and the first 3 books of Rosenburg's "Guardians of the Flame".  If you are lucky you can get the hardcover with all 3 novels in it.  After book 3, imagine the rest of the story -- the rest of the books are good, but not as good as the first 3.
<br />

<br />
For Sci Fi, try some James P Hogan, in particular:
<br />
"Code of the Lifemaker"
<br />
"Thrice Upon a Time"
<br />
"Inherit the Stars"
<br />

<br />
The less you know about a JPH book before you read it, the better.  I'd even advise you not to read the jacket cover.
<br />

<br />
Also try an Ian M Banks "culture" novel:
<br />
"Consider Phelbas"
<br />
"Use of Weapons"
<br />
"Excession"
<br />

<br />
Naturally, Douglas Adam's:
<br />
"The Hitchhiker's Guild to the Galaxy"
<br />

<br />
Grab some classics, like CS Lewis's Narnia series.
<br />

<br />
For some different fantasy, if pulpy, try out the Amber series.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
