                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I enjoyed the Stephen King Dark Tower Series of Books. Not his usual horror, but then not a comedy either.
<br />

<br />
I read Fatherland by Robert Harris not too long ago. I understand the film they made of it with Rutger Hauer and Miranda Richardson was dire but the book is excellent. The what if the Nazi's had won the war is only a back drop to the story, but what unfolds is quite chilling, especially when you realise some of the principal characters actually existed.
<br />

<br />
If you enjoyed Terry Pratchett his Guards of the Watch books are my favorite, I think Guards Guards was the first, Jingo is another.
<br />

<br />
Thrillers, Jeffrey Deavers The Bone Collector, also a film was good, but its sequel, the Coffin Dancer had a very original twist too it.
<br />

<br />
If you can get your hands on a book called Messiah by Boris Starling, I would recommend it. I never read the book, but the BBC adaptation of it (also exceptional, if you can get that do so, but dont bother with the sequels they were just the characters used by the BBC, the plots are no where near as good). The 'real' sequel to the book, Storm, by Boris Starling is a good read, but not as good as Messiah.
<br />

<br />
Finally if thats not enough and you want something a bit more gruesome, but mesmerising, funny and compelling, try Clive Barkers Books of Blood. They are 6 volumes of short stories. I never thought Barkers novels were anywhere as good as these short stories.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
