<br />

<br />
I agree as well, but I prefer the Fountainhead for first time Ayn Rand readers because it's a better story and less of an intellectual excersise. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Yakk wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Read The Fountainhead, but realize you are reading propoganda. Treat it like you would reading the foundation myth of a religious sect. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Garbage. It's a novel just like any other with it's own ideas and the worldview of the author comes out just like it would with any other book. I certainly wouldn't call 'The Handmaid's Tale' by Margret Atwood propaganda simply because it deals with social and economic themes. Many people do take Ayn Rand very seriously but that certainly doesn't detract from the fact that it's a good novel with many original ideas that can lead to interesting and varied discussions. I mean is the 'Lion, the Witch, and the Wardrobe' Christian propaganda because it's an allegory of the crucifixion and it's author wrote many non-fiction books on Christianity? Hardly.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />When a government has ceased to protect the lives, liberty and property of the people, from whom its legitimate powers are derived, and for the advancement of whose happiness it was instituted, and so far from being a guarantee for the enjoyment of those inestimable and inalienable rights, becomes an instrument in the hands of evil rulers for their oppression. - Declaration of Independence of the State of Texas.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
