                        <tr>
                                <td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><a href="viewtopic.php?p=98908#98908"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Fri Mar 11, 2005 1:05 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: </span></td>
                                <td align="right" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=98908"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>    </td></tr></table></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Twizlewink wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Yakk wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Read The Fountainhead, but realize you are reading propoganda. Treat it like you would reading the foundation myth of a religious sect. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Garbage. It's a novel just like any other with it's own ideas and the worldview of the author comes out just like it would with any other book. I certainly wouldn't call 'The Handmaid's Tale' by Margret Atwood propaganda simply because it deals with social and economic themes. Many people do take Ayn Rand very seriously but that certainly doesn't detract from the fact that it's a good novel with many original ideas that can lead to interesting and varied discussions. I mean is the 'Lion, the Witch, and the Wardrobe' Christian propaganda because it's an allegory of the crucifixion and it's author wrote many non-fiction books on Christianity? Hardly.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Ayn Rand was a true believer, who wrote a story that generates true believers.  She writes of a world in which the beliefs she believes in work perfectly.
<br />

<br />
And yes, CS Lewis's LTW&TW contains some religious propoganda.  It isn't nearly as strong as Ayn Rand's fiction.
<br />

<br />
When you read fiction books that are intended to change your belief structure, be aware of it.  Repeating someone else's ideas in your head without filtering or criticism is somewhat dangerous.  Reading those ideas with thought and criticism is good and healthy.
<br />

<br />
Some authors write because they find an idea interesting.  Some authors write to make an entertaining yarn.  Others write because they want to change your beliefs and thought patterns.  Ayn Rand's books are intended to generate converts.
<br />

<br />
Robert A Heilien's is another one of those authors -- he started writing juvenile SF because he found them better for molding people's minds than writing non-fiction pieces about society and technology.
<br />

<br />
The number of Randites out there who take A.R.'s philosophy as revieled truth tells you something about her writings.  All I'm saying is, read it with a guarded mind, unless you are looking for a random new belief system.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
