		<td width="150" align="left" valign="top" class="row1"><a name="99194"></a><span class="name"><span class="usercolor">Twizlewink</span></span><div class="gensmall"><img src="images/ranks/rank_7.gif" alt="<b><center><font color=black>Mindbender</font></b></center>" title="<b><center><font color=black>Mindbender</font></b></center>" border="0" /><br /><b><center><font color=black>Mindbender</font></b></center></div><div align="center"><img src="images/avatars/database/600avatars/093.gif" alt="Avatar" border="0" /></div><br /><div align="left" class="gensmall">Gender:&nbsp;Unknown</div></td>
                <td class="row1" width="100%" height="28" valign="top"><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
                        <tr>
                                <td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><a href="viewtopic.php?p=99194#99194"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Tue Mar 15, 2005 8:25 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: </span></td>
                                <td align="right" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=99194"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>    </td></tr></table></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Yakk wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">When you read fiction books that are intended to change your belief structure, be aware of it.  Repeating someone else's ideas in your head without filtering or criticism is somewhat dangerous.  Reading those ideas with thought and criticism is good and healthy.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
It's very difficult not to be aware of it if you read the introduction - she makes her aims perfectly clear. Her entire philosophy of art is the idea that it should represent man as he should be instead of as he is, or for other forms of artistic merit. I guess I don't see it as propaganda only because she makes her goals and aims very clear and in no way attempts to decieve the reader into believing anything else. Her goal is to express her interpretation of the ideal human being and the ideal world and that's very clearly stated in the introduction. I think you're abusing the word propaganda to such a broad extreme that even acedemic papers would qualify. I mean is a book on Einstein's physics propaganda because it's trying to change your believe structure on how you interpret the physical universe? Your definition is too broad and incorrectly catagorizes many things that are simply not seen as propaganda including the 'Chronicles of Narnia' and I think you'd have a hard time convincing anyone of it. 
<br />

<br />
On top of that I'd argue that 'The Fountainhead' certainly was written with the intent of convincing anyone to change their mind. Her non-fiction and 'Atlas Shrugged' moreso (I'm thinking of John Galt's speach to the world paticularly) are definitely geared more towards attempting to build her worldview - but again she discloses that fact in the introduction. She isn't plying off emotional impulses to attempt to suspend rational thought in order to convert other people and that to me encompasses the true essence of propaganda. She's definitely making an arguement though and expressing her opinion on how the world should be - but again that's her philosophy of art and it's very much grounded in classical principles. The ancient greeks for example felt much the same way. 
<br />

<br />
Naturally I recommend reading everything with a critical eye and I certainly don't ageree with Ayn Rand on her worldview, but I don't fault her for expressing it through art either. The Fountainhead is a good novel that can keep you very interested from start to finish because it has interesting charecters, and some great quotes with a clear and interesting plot. I love the story of a man struggling against all odds to change the world. It's a good book to read to challenge you intellectually as well as telling a good story (something I can't say about L. Ron Hubbard's work).</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />When a government has ceased to protect the lives, liberty and property of the people, from whom its legitimate powers are derived, and for the advancement of whose happiness it was instituted, and so far from being a guarantee for the enjoyment of those inestimable and inalienable rights, becomes an instrument in the hands of evil rulers for their oppression. - Declaration of Independence of the State of Texas.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
